Low-frequency Stoneley waves in porous rocks are affected by fluid mobility (permeability/viscosity) because it governs fluid leakage into/from the borehole, impacting wave propagation velocity and attenuation. Other options (B, C, D) are unrelated to the physical mechanisms of these waves.  

\boxed{A}

The reflection coefficient magnitude is calculated using the formula\( R = \frac{Z_2 - Z_1}{Z_2 + Z_1} \), where \( Z = \rho v \). For Layer 1, \( Z_1 = 2300 \times 3000 = 6,900,000 \, \text{kg/(m²·s)} \). For Layer 2, \( Z_2 = 2500 \times 5000 = 12,500,000 \, \text{kg/(m²·s)} \). Substituting these values:  
\( R = \frac{12,500,000 - 6,900,000}{12,500,000 + 6,900,000} = \frac{5,600,000}{19,400,000} \approx 0.288 \). The magnitude is approximately 0.29.  

\boxed{A}
